You should avoid remembering passwords when possible. But, at least in 2025, you probably still need at least one. Maybe it's the password for your laptop, or Bitwarden. It's important that this kind of "master password" is both very strong (generated from a process with lots of random free choice) and also very memorable. I've spent a lot of time thinking about the best way to achieve this, and the result is below: "passpoems"? "passverses"? Let's go with "pacewords".

                    </select>
                </div>
                <div class="control-group">
                    <label for="feet-count">Feet per Line:</label>
                    <select id="feet-count">
                        <option value="1">1</option>
                        <option value="2">2</option>
                        <option value="3" selected>3</option>
                        <option value="4">4</option>
                        <option value="5">5</option>
                    </select>
                </div>
                <div class="control-group">
                    <label>&nbsp;</label>
                    <button id="generate">Generate Password</button>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="output" id="output">Click "Generate Password" to create a poem</div>
            <div class="entropy" id="entropy"></div>

    attachEventListeners() {
        const generateBtn = this.shadowRoot.getElementById('generate');
        generateBtn.addEventListener('click', () => this.generatePassword());
    }
    getSecureRandom(max) {
        const randomBuffer = new Uint32Array(1);
        crypto.getRandomValues(randomBuffer);
        return randomBuffer[0] % max;
    }
    getRandomTrochee() {
        return this.trochees[this.getSecureRandom(this.trochees.length)];
    }
    getRandomRhymingPair() {
        return this.rhymingPairs[this.getSecureRandom(this.rhymingPairs.length)];
    }
    generateLine(feetCount, rhymeWord) {
        const words = [];
        for (let i = 0; i < feetCount - 1; i++) {
            words.push(this.getRandomTrochee());
        }
        words.push(rhymeWord);
        return words.join(' ');
    }
    generatePassword() {
        const rhymeScheme = this.shadowRoot.getElementById('rhyme-scheme').value;
        const feetCount = parseInt(this.shadowRoot.getElementById('feet-count').value);
        let lines = [];
        switch (rhymeScheme) {
            case 'AA': {
                const [rhyme1, rhyme2] = this.getRandomRhymingPair();
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhyme1));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhyme2));
                break;
            }
            case 'AABB': {
                const [rhymeA1, rhymeA2] = this.getRandomRhymingPair();
                const [rhymeB1, rhymeB2] = this.getRandomRhymingPair();
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeA1));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeA2));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeB1));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeB2));
                break;
            }
            case 'ABBA': {
                const [rhymeA1, rhymeA2] = this.getRandomRhymingPair();
                const [rhymeB1, rhymeB2] = this.getRandomRhymingPair();
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeA1));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeB1));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeB2));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeA2));
                break;
            }
            case 'ABAB': {
                const [rhymeA1, rhymeA2] = this.getRandomRhymingPair();
                const [rhymeB1, rhymeB2] = this.getRandomRhymingPair();
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeA1));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeB1));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeA2));
                lines.push(this.generateLine(feetCount, rhymeB2));
                break;
            }
        }
        const poem = lines.join('\n');
        this.shadowRoot.getElementById('output').textContent = poem;
        // Calculate entropy
        const entropy = this.calculateEntropy(rhymeScheme, feetCount);
        this.shadowRoot.getElementById('entropy').textContent =
            `Entropy: ${entropy.toFixed(2)} bits`;
    }
    calculateEntropy(rhymeScheme, feetCount) {
        const bitsPerFoot = Math.log2(this.trochees.length);
        const bitsPerRhyme = Math.log2(this.rhymingPairs.length);
        const bitsFromRhymes = bitsPerRhyme * rhymeScheme.length / 2;
        const bitsFromFeet = (feetCount - 1) * bitsPerFoot * rhymeScheme.length;
        return bitsFromRhymes + bitsFromFeet;
    }
    // Method to set custom word lists
    setWordLists(trochees, rhymingPairs) {
        this.trochees = trochees;
        this.rhymingPairs = rhymingPairs;
    }
}
customElements.define('trochaic-password-generator', TrochaicPasswordGenerator);

These poems are generated entirely in your browser based on wordlists you can see by looking at the page's source code. They have some nice properties:

1. It's easy to get passwords with plenty of entropy (typically you want at least 75 bits or so; 128 for the truly paranoid)
2. The poems rhyme.
3. They (usually) scan pretty well. I chose the word list to fit nicely into trochaic meter: Everything is either a trochee (like **Op**en) or a dactyl (like **Se**same), except that the rhymes are a bit more flexible.

You may need to re-roll a couple times to get a password you like. This is fine; as long as you don't do it _loads_ of times, you'll only decrease the entropy slightly.
